{{- /*
config-secrets-key.tmpl — the machine-local AES key that encrypts the secrets
prompted by .chezmoi.toml.tmpl (luksPassphraseCipher / mokPasswordCipher) so
they are stored in ~/.config/chezmoi/chezmoi.toml as ciphertext, never
plaintext. The key lives ONLY in the user keyring (Secret Service on Linux,
Keychain on macOS) under service=chezmoi-config-secrets / user=<username>; it
is generated by the .install-prerequisites.{sh,ps1} read-source-state hook,
which runs before chezmoi ever renders the config template on `init`.

Read FAIL-SOFT via `chezmoi secret keyring get` in a subshell: chezmoi's
built-in `keyring` template function hard-errors when no keyring daemon is
reachable (headless, TTY, container, CI — it even tries to exec dbus-launch),
which would break every render there. This wrapper yields an empty string
instead, and callers treat an empty key as "secret unavailable" and take
their skip path. `.chezmoi.executable` (not a bare `chezmoi`) keeps this
working when the running binary is not on PATH.

Rotation/loss: a lost or rotated keyring entry cannot decrypt previously
stored ciphertexts — decryptAES then yields garbage (or a render error). To
recover, re-prompt with `chezmoi init --data=false` (or delete the *Cipher
keys from ~/.config/chezmoi/chezmoi.toml and re-run `chezmoi init`).
*/ -}}
{{- if ne .chezmoi.os "windows" -}}
{{-   output "sh" "-c" (printf "%q secret keyring get --service=chezmoi-config-secrets --user=%q 2>/dev/null || true" .chezmoi.executable .chezmoi.username) | trim -}}
{{- end -}}
